                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">With the Nintendo DS to hit next week and the Playstation Portable (PSP) in another month or so, which will you guys be buying?
<br />

<br />
I'm definitely buying a Nintendo DS but I'm undecided about the PSP. While I can afford both I figure 90% of the respective game libraries will be the same. The two major reasons pushing me into buying only a Nintendo DS is that most games will be out for both systems more likely than not and my old library of Gameboy games. 
<br />

<br />
Both systems seem to have a lot in common such as wireless communication using WIFI to communicate with other game systems and the ability to display 3d graphics. 
<br />

<br />

<br />
Nintendo DS.
<br />

<br />
The dual screen (DS stands for dual screen in the name) on this looks very interesting and should add a higher level of control in some games when coupled with the touch screen feature on the bottom screen. I do feel the touch screen is an overhyped feature though. I'm not saying it won't be useful but I just think it's overhyped. I'm much more excited by the dual screens.
<br />

<br />
It's 3d capabilites are not as high as that of the PSP but it holds it's own. I mean, the ability to display Nintendo64 quality graphics on a gaming system is plenty good in my opinion. After all, it's the gameplay that is the most important part of a game and not game graphics.
<br />

<br />
Another strong point IMHO is the fact that it has a long battery life. About double that of the PSP. 
<br />

<br />
While some may not like the clamshell design of the DS at least it protects both of your screens from damage while being dragged around. After all, you DO want to be lugging it around with you or you defeat the whole purpose of a portable gaming system. 
<br />

<br />

<br />
Playstation Portable.
<br />

<br />
Graphics. This thing has what is described as a Playstation 2 type graphics shrunk down. While it has only one screen they are saying it's a much higher qaulity LCD than the one in the DS. Again, the most important part of any game is gameplay but good graphics never hurt. <img src="images/smiles/icon_smile.gif" alt="icon_smile.gif" border="0" />
<br />

<br />
Higher amount of space available for game data. While I'm not sure what the space is on the UMD (some sort of mini dvd) it's gotta be more than a cartridge. 
<br />

<br />
The PSP also sports the ability to play back movies. However I think this is a hugely overrated feature. Who in their right mind is going to pay another $20 bucks or whatever for a portable version of a movie when they own the DVD version. Heck, there are portable DVD players with 7" screens that are only about $150 bucks that will play normal DVD's. You can't burn UMD's due to piracy concerns obviously. More likey the video playback feature will be used for FMV narrations inside of games. 
<br />

<br />
The reported 5-6 hour battery life on this sucker would make this a breaker for long trips. The DS has over 10 hours of battery life per charge while the PSP has about 5 hours per charge. 
<br />

<br />
Another negative for early adopters is the fact that it's stated they will most likely be moving to 65nm fabrication of the chips used in the PSP or less likely to change the design of the chip itself to reduce power usage as opposed to the current 90nm process. That means that early adopters will have a perfectly fine PSP BUT with crappy battery life compared to later PSP systems. Way to go Sony, kicking your early adopters in the rear as opposed to releasing a more complete product.  
<br />

<br />
The PSP has a very sleek and nice looking design. I actually like how it looks. Hope the cover protecting the LCD is replaceable as it's bound to get a few nicks and scratches as anyone with older gameboys can attest to.</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br /><span style="font-style: italic">On the other hand, if your reaction to something I say boils down to "You didn't choose MY side, make MY choice," well, you're not looking for information, you're looking for someone to tell you how smart you are thinking the way you do. --</span> <span style="font-weight: bold">Ed Stroligo</span></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
