                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">My initial impressions on my Gameboy DS. I have only one DS game and that is Super Mario 64 DS.
<br />

<br />
The feel of it is quite comfortable for the most part. However, the top half of the bottom part of the shell is not flush with the bottom part. It creates a slightly edged area that can be uncomfortable holding it in certain positions. It's also quite heavy compared to a Gameboy Advance or Gameboy SP. If you're used to a Gameboy SP's weight, prepare for something much heavier. It's also quite large for a portable gaming system. To tell you the truth, I was expecting something akin to a Gameboy Advance but doublestacked (not SP version). It will fit in an adult sized person's pants pocket or a purse or handbag but it's definitely not gonna fit in a kid's pocket. 
<br />

<br />
Control wise it's not bad. The cross control, shoulder and front buttoms feel exactly as they should. However, they made a huge mistake in not including an analogue stick for 3D games. While controlling your character in 3D with the touchscreen is serviceable I ran into frequent times when my thumb would reach the edge of the screen and I'd have to lift my thumb and relocate it at a more centered position on the screen. The lack of tactile feedback can be annoying at times when you need fine control or in a critical area and you just hit the edge of the touchscreen. You don't run into this problem with an analogue stick because you obviously can only move the stick so far before you know to ease up cause you can't move it any further. Other than that, I think the controls work fine. 
<br />

<br />
I do have one concern and it's how well the touchscreen will hold up with the battering it's sure to take from heavy abuse. $150 is not a light investment and it'd SUCK to have the touchscreen conk out on you after a year or so of use.
<br />

<br />
Backwards compatibility with only Gamboy Advance games is puzzling. They can easily put in compatibility with the older Gameboy and Gameboy Color games. If the system can display 3D graphics at a similar level to the N64 (slightly better IMHO on early games) and it can play Gameboy Advance games then it SHOULD be able to emulate the older Gameboy games. That aside, the Gameboy Advance games look great. They look better than on the Gameboy Advance due to the higher quality screens. 
<br />

<br />
Overall I'm satisfied with my purchase. It's a nice system with a few minor quirks.I feel there are more positives than negatives. I can't wait for more games to utilize the dual screens.</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br /><span style="font-style: italic">On the other hand, if your reaction to something I say boils down to "You didn't choose MY side, make MY choice," well, you're not looking for information, you're looking for someone to tell you how smart you are thinking the way you do. --</span> <span style="font-weight: bold">Ed Stroligo</span></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
