                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">90% of the games on the PSP upon release will be rehashes of PS and PS2 games anyways. I'm not saying they aren't fun games. Not saying they won't look good. However, the initial releases will all be formulaic or ports. I'm leaning towards getting both, however, with the word of a newer model PSP at the end of next year with better battery life why in hell would I spend 200+ for the PSP and shell out another 30-35 for the games. That's about $260 after tax. After all, no one buys just the console alone. They usually buy at least one game with it. 
<br />

<br />
Aside from the forementioned control quirks which sometimes hinder the gameplay, Super Mario 64 DS has been nearly as fun as the original. Having extra star challenges is great too. The original N64 game had 120 stars to collect, the DS version has 150 stars. It's really not as bad as some would have you believe. As for Final Fantasy, I love the franchise (except for <img src="images/smiles/icon_cool.gif" alt="icon_cool.gif" border="0" />. 
<br />

<br />
As for movie playback on the PSP, you DO understand that the PSP uses UMD a proprietary format similar to what the Gamecube used. It's basically a mini DVD like format. You won't be able to play your normal DVD's with it. I'm not shelling out $20 for the DVD's and then shelling out $20 more for a PSP version of the movie. I can just buy one of those hard drive based MP3 players that also plays divx files if that's the case. I can rip my whole DVD collection and download it onto the MP3 player and play them whenever without added cost. Just some time for the ripping but you can just leave your computer overnight to rip & encode to divx. 
<br />

<br />
As I wrote before, don't expect Sony to release a UMD burner for ripped movies or MP3's because of piracy concerns and money. They don't want anyone being able to burn the discs because someone somewhere will find a way to crack the games and pirate them. They won't allow MP3 discs to be burned because then you won't buy their way way overpriced Memory Sticks to load MP3's onto. 
<br />

<br />
I'm not trying to bash the PSP, I do plan to get one eventually. However, media playback is one of it's most over rated features. Marchitecture at it's best. Marchitecture is marketing + architecture. Marketing hype coupled with a new "ooh" feature that will ultimately be barey used. The reality is that if you really plan on playing movies there are better devices out there in hard drive based MP3 players that also will hold your whole MP3 collection. You also won't need to carry discs for the movies as they are at a minimum large enough to hold 20GB of movies and MP3's. Not to mention the fact they are smaller and more easily fit in your pocket than the PSP will.
<br />

<br />
I forgot to note the analogue stick on the PSP. That IMHO is THE biggest design/feature win for the PSP. A 3D game simply controls a ton better with an analogue control vs the touchscreen. The screen is doable but not preferable. Although FPS's such as the Metroid Prime Hunters demo that comes with the DS is actually quite well done on the DS's touchscreen. It looks quirky and unintuitive but play it a few times and it really does work great.</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br /><span style="font-style: italic">On the other hand, if your reaction to something I say boils down to "You didn't choose MY side, make MY choice," well, you're not looking for information, you're looking for someone to tell you how smart you are thinking the way you do. --</span> <span style="font-weight: bold">Ed Stroligo</span></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
